    "created_at": "2018-07-13T01:32:00Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-07-13T01:32:00Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "The groupby piece here is a red herring. As @gfyoung mentioned frame division will only work if the column names are aligned. Consider the following:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nIn [9]: df = pd.DataFrame(np.ones((2, 2)), columns=['a', 'b'])\r\n\r\nIn [10]: df2 = pd.DataFrame(np.ones((2, 2)), columns=['c', 'd'])\r\n\r\nIn [11]: df / df2\r\nOut[11]: \r\n    a   b   c   d\r\n0 NaN NaN NaN NaN\r\n1 NaN NaN NaN NaN\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo in short this is not a bug. \r\n\r\nI don't think it's possible to cover the use case you are looking for with the built in operator, but you can use the frame div method to get the desired output, i.e.:\r\n\r\n```python\r\nIn [7]: df.div(pd.Series([1, 2]), axis=0)\r\nOut[7]: \r\n     a    b\r\n0  1.0  1.0\r\n1  0.5  0.5\r\n```"
  }
